column21:
The data I get from my G502 spectrum or a G402 does not seem to fit the hidpp20_led_sw_ctrl_led_info structure.

G502 spectrum

00 02 03 00 03 07 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
01 03 03 00 03 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00


G402

00 02 03 00 03 07 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
01 04 01 00 80 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00

With this structure:
struct hidpp20_led_sw_ctrl_led_info {
	uint8_t index;
	uint16_t type;
	uint8_t physical_count;
	uint16_t caps;
	uint8_t nvconfig_caps;
} __attribute__((packed));

That gives types 0x0203, 0x0303 or 0x0401. And zero nvconfig caps, although, on the G502 spectrum, functions 6 and 7 can control if the DPI LEDs stay on (LED 0 only). It would fit better with a 8 bit type.

@bentiss it's a year later and afaict this hasn't been pushed into the kernel anywhere? Did this get lost?

Not really. Each of my attempts to push it and ask for feedback resulted in a /dev/null answer. So I still need to push it.
But I agree, in the meantime, it would be a nice feature to have.

I started to play with this for the steelseries driver today. It works well to convert to/from the macros. The thing that got me back to this PR was that I was looking into why I got "UNKNOWN" as the button action for some buttons. Turns out that ratbagd converts the action if it is of type KEY:
	if (type == RATBAG_BUTTON_ACTION_TYPE_KEY)
		type = RATBAG_BUTTON_ACTION_TYPE_UNKNOWN;

So _KEY is already non-functional and I wanted to start on getting the (single key press) macro working instead of fixing the old way. With this patch I can finally assign keys in Piper. (No modifiers yet, but could be added).
The issue I saw with "RESERVED" in ratbagctl seems to have gone away.

